File: Populations in France, Germany, Britain, Japan, Sweden, and the US widely believed death and infection figures to be higher than recorded, according to the study, which polled 1,000 people in each nation. JOHANNESBURG - The Health Department reported 115 more COVID-19 related deaths in South Africa, taking the death toll to 14,678. KwaZulu-Natal reported 15 deaths, 43 from Gauteng, 12 from Eastern Cape, 18 from Free State, four from Western Cape, 11 from Northern Cape and 12 from Limpopo. READ: COVID-19: African countries sign groundbreaking vaccine agreement SA's COVID-19 recoveries stand at 557,818, which translates to a recovery rate of 88%. Health Minister Zweli Mkhize says the threat of a second wave remains very real. He's urged South Africans to be responsible and to enforce social distancing, hand washing and the wearing of masks.  Health Media Release 4 September 2020.Pages V1 (1) by eNCA.com on Scribd 